According to the plot of (αhυ)1/2 against (h
                              υ
                           ) energy [56], band gap energy of pure CQDs is 2.56 eV while the optimized 10%F-10%B co-doped CQD exhibits Eg=2.25 eV (see Figs. 4b). Besides, band gap values for CQDs containing different amounts of boron and fluorine including 1–1, 5–5, 7.5–7.5, 12.5–12.5, and 15%−15% of fluorine and boron are 2.65, 2.62, 2.60, 2.59, and 2.78 eV, respectively, obtained by extrapolation (Fig. S1). In fact, the doped fluorine and boron are hosted as the impurity elements inside CQD framework, which formed some mid-gap energy levels between valence and conduction bands of CQD. As a result, the introduction of F and B elements within the CQD structure increases harvesting of visible light and narrows band gap. Such mid-gaps expedite the electron and hole separation, increase exciton lifetime, and thereby boost photocatalytic capacity of carbon materials upon visible light radiation.

The particle diameters and morphology characteristics of pure and F,B co-doped CQDs with different F and B percentages, are examined by FE-SEM images (Fig. 5
                           ). As can be seen, all of the CQDs show an accumulated and chunky surface forming larger particles, which are probably due to the fact that they are agglomerated during sample preparation for FE-SEM imaging. It should be noted that these CQDs are agglomerated in the solid state, but they have a high dispersion in water as displayed in Fig. 6
                           a which seems as if they are completely dissolved in water. FE-SEM images mainly show well-developed nanoscale, semi-spherical, and layered morphology.
